	<section class="grid project-header">
		<div class="col-6_md-7_sm-8_xs-12 project-textblock">
			<div class="titleimage-container">
				<img src="img/project_headers/estuary.svg" alt="estuary.fm" class="page-header_title">
			</div>
			<div class="project-desc">
				<h3>CASE STUDY</h3>
			</div>

			<p>Research and exploratory work towards designing and building a mobile app to help music listeners find new artists, genres and music styles.</p>
		</div>

		<div class="col-6_md-5_sm-4_xs-12">
			<div class="project-headerline"> </div>
		</div>
	</section>


	<section class="grid align-center page-section">
			<div class="col-2_sm-2_xs-12">
				<h5>OVERVIEW</h5>
			</div>
			<div class="col-7_sm-9">
				<div class="title-headerline"> </div>
			</div>

		<div class="grid align-center">
			<div class="col-7_lg-8_sm-10_xs-12">
				<div class="page-paragraph_block">
					<p>Music discovery can be hard, many of us rely on online blogs, recommendations from friends, playlists, FM radio, or whatever tools your music streaming platform of choice offers. Unfortunately these options are often unreliable, repetitive, or aren’t personalized enough, making it harder to find new, underground or exciting artists and songs to fall in love with. This project is an attempt to solve some of these frustrations, by <b>giving users a tool that allows them to customize their different tastes in music, find new (and less mainstream) artists, easily create playlists full of recommendations, and encourage more music sharing.</b></p>
					<p>As a personal project, I was able to focus on a few aspects of UX and product design that I don’t get the opportunities to apply or practice everyday. My main goals were to create a focused and thorough user experience by zeroing in on process, documentation, problem solving, and iteration. This meant spending more time on user flows, functionality and interaction design elements rather than branding, design systems, or aesthetics. <b>The following content is a work in progress, documented and formatted to show thinking and process.</b></p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>


	<section class="grid align-center">
		<div class="col-12 page-section">
			<img src="img/estuary/est-sketches.png" alt="ideas and sketches">
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="grid align-center page-section">
		<div class="col-2_sm-2_xs-12">
			<h5>PROCESS</h5>
		</div>
		<div class="col-7_sm-9">
			<div class="title-headerline"> </div>
		</div>

		<div class="grid align-center">
			<div class="col-7_lg-8_sm-10_xs-12">
				<div class="page-paragraph_block">
					<p>During my research phase, I discovered a number of existing tools to both take inspiration from, and analyse each of their success and failures. <a href="https://magicplaylist.co/" target="_blank">MagicPlaylist</a> for instance, shows exactly how simple playlist generation can be, and <a href="https://musicroamer.com/" target="_blank">MusicRoamer</a> does an excellent job visualizing the relationships between related artists. These sites are <b>interesting tools to use and explore but neither have a comprehensive toolset or a wide offering of different connected services.</b></p>
					<p>I started exploring what a platform would look like that took the best things these tools had to offer and combined them in a way that was cohesive and interconnected. Some simple brainstorming with pen and paper, (as seen above) allowed me to <b>quickly ideate solutions, features, pain points, and interactions.</b> I identified the core functionality that would be necessary for a <b>MVP feature-set including the ability to create and share lists of related artists, an easy tool to generate a playlist based on an artist or list, and a way to view and organize multiple lists.</b> From there I was able to generate a few other features that would both support and help connect the core features, including the ability to view popular lists or artists, preview an artist's work within app, and a tool that would allow users to input detailed likes and dislikes to generate a personalized list of artist recommendations.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>


	<section class="grid align-center">
		<div class="col-12 page-section">
			<img src="img/estuary/estuary_userflow.png" alt="user flow breakdown">
		</div>
	</section>


	<section class="grid align-center page-section">
		<div class="col-2_sm-2_xs-12">
			<h5>DESIGN</h5>
		</div>
		<div class="col-7_sm-9">
			<div class="title-headerline"> </div>
		</div>

		<div class="grid align-center">
			<div class="col-7_lg-8_sm-10_xs-12">
				<div class="page-paragraph_block">
					<p>Using these initial concepts as a launching point, I created a rough draft of a <b>user flow map highlighting the different views and interactions</b>. While fairly high-level, this allowed me to quickly and easily understand the scope of the project, and identify which interactions would be needed for each view. This made creating wireframes significantly faster and easier, as I already knew which interactions were needed on each screen, and how they all flowed together. Taking a few of these wireframes, and <b>translating them into full designs with real content allowed me to really test my initial assumptions</b> as well as make some branding and visual design decisions. I also referred to Material Design guidelines, as well as took some inspiration from music streaming apps like Apple Music during this phase to better understand mobile design standards for music apps. <b>This led to a lot of iteration</b>, tweaking colors, font weights, and layouts to better fit both the content and the visual tone I was trying to achieve.</p>

					<p>While <b>the visual style and branding elements are still works-in-progress</b>, there are a few fundamental concepts that will be carried through to the final product. The color palette is calm and welcoming, using warm tones and earthy colors to encourage the user to explore and create. The use of wide font styles, while challenging on smaller screen sizes, brings some personality and charm to the overall look and feel. Finally, the use of drop shadows not only borrows some visual language from popular app design, but is used as another tool to separate content, highlight actionable elements, and support a consistent visual hierarchy of both actions and content alike.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>


	<section class="grid align-center">
		<div class="col-12 page-section">
			<img src="img/estuary/est-wireframes1.png" alt="wireframes">
